faqs:
  - q: "When is a German Shepherd considered senior?"
    a: "German Shepherds are a large breed with a relatively short lifespan (typically 9–13 years), so they cross into 'senior' early — usually around 7 years, sometimes from 6. Large breeds age faster than small ones, and a Shepherd's hard-working joints, deep chest and famously delicate gut mean the senior dietary shift (easier digestion, joint support, muscle-sparing protein) is worth making sooner rather than later. Don't wait for a birthday: watch for a greying muzzle, stiffer mornings, a slowing pace and — the breed-specific marker to take seriously — any weakness, scuffing or wobble in the back legs, which can be the first sign of degenerative myelopathy."
  - q: "How much should I feed a senior German Shepherd per day?"
    a: "Less than you fed them as a working-age adult. A senior Shepherd's metabolism slows and activity drops, so the 300–500g of dry food a day a younger 30–40kg GSD needs comes down for a steadier older dog. But the honest method is to weigh meals on a kitchen scale, weigh your dog monthly, and keep the ribs easily felt without losing the muscle over the spine and hindquarters. For a big dog, fresh feeding adds up fast — feeding a 35kg senior entirely on frozen fresh can run to several pounds a day, which is why we lean toward shelf-stable fresh, air-dried and cold-pressed routes for this breed. Whatever you feed, split it across two (or more) smaller meals — a deep-chested breed should never gorge one big bowl."
  - q: "What should I look for in food for an older German Shepherd?"
    a: "Five things, the first two carried straight from the breed's lifelong brief. High digestibility above all — Shepherds have the highest rate of exocrine pancreatic insufficiency (EPI) of any breed, and even those without it have sensitive guts, so gently-cooked fresh, air-dried or cold-pressed recipes with named single proteins beat high-heat extruded biscuit. A limited-ingredient, often grain-free recipe to calm the skin allergies and loose stools the breed is prone to. Then the senior layer: generous high-quality named protein (muscle over the spine and hindquarters is what keeps a Shepherd standing as it ages); joint support (glucosamine, chondroitin, omega-3 for the hip and elbow dysplasia this breed is a poster child for); and a recipe you can split across smaller meals to respect the deep-chested bloat risk."
  - q: "Why does muscle and protein matter so much for a senior German Shepherd specifically?"
    a: "Because of the back legs. German Shepherds are the breed most associated with degenerative myelopathy (DM) — a progressive, non-painful disease of the spinal cord that slowly weakens the hindquarters, causing scuffing paws, a wobbly gait and eventually difficulty standing. Diet can't stop DM (there's no cure), but two food levers genuinely help a dog stay mobile longer: staying lean, so weak hindquarters aren't dragging extra weight, and feeding generous high-quality protein to fight the age-related muscle loss (sarcopenia) that DM and reduced activity both accelerate. Strong muscle around a failing nerve supply keeps a dog walking; lost muscle takes mobility away faster than the disease alone. If you see any hind-leg weakness, scuffing or wobble, see your vet — but lean, well-muscled body condition is the best dietary insurance either way."
  - q: "My senior German Shepherd has a sensitive stomach and loose stools — can food help?"
    a: "Very much so — for this breed it's often the whole game. German Shepherds have notoriously delicate digestion and the highest breed incidence of exocrine pancreatic insufficiency (EPI), where the pancreas stops making enough digestive enzymes and food passes through poorly digested (classic signs: large, pale, greasy stools, ravenous appetite but weight loss). A highly digestible, limited-ingredient recipe with a single named protein and moderate fat reduces the load on a struggling gut, and gently-cooked or cold-pressed foods are absorbed more easily than high-heat kibble. If your senior Shepherd is losing weight despite eating well, or passing voluminous greasy stools, ask your vet about an EPI blood test (TLI) — it's manageable with enzyme supplementation plus the right diet, but food alone won't fix true EPI."
  - q: "Should I switch my senior German Shepherd to a 'senior' labelled food?"
    a: "Not automatically — the 'senior' label isn't regulated and quality varies hugely. What matters is the profile: high digestibility for the sensitive gut, generous named-meat protein to hold muscle over the spine and hindquarters, moderate fat that won't strain the pancreas, joint support, and a limited-ingredient base for skin and stool. Beware low-protein 'senior' recipes — the old 'less protein for old dogs' line is an outdated myth, and for a breed at risk of muscle-wasting hindquarter disease it's exactly the wrong move. A high-quality fresh, air-dried or grain-free adult food that hits those marks can beat a mediocre 'senior' one. Whatever you choose, transition gradually over 7–10 days; a sensitive Shepherd gut punishes sudden change."
  - q: "Does a senior German Shepherd still need to worry about bloat?"
    a: "Yes — the deep-chested anatomy that makes German Shepherds prone to bloat (gastric dilatation-volvulus, GDV) doesn't go away with age, and an older dog handles the emergency less well. Feed two or more smaller meals rather than one large bowl, don't let your dog gulp food or water, avoid vigorous exercise for an hour either side of meals, and use a slow-feeder bowl if your Shepherd bolts its dinner. Raised bowls were once advised but the evidence is now mixed, so don't assume they help. Know the signs — a swollen, hard belly, unproductive retching, restlessness and distress — and treat them as a life-threatening emergency: go straight to a vet, day or night."
