<h2>How to Choose for Your Senior German Shepherd</h2>

<p>There's no single winner — it depends on your dog, your budget and your kitchen:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Sensitive stomach, loose stools or suspected EPI?</strong> Favour the most digestible, limited-ingredient, single-protein recipes — Years and the gently-cooked fresh brands are gentlest on a delicate Shepherd gut. If weight loss accompanies a big appetite or stools are pale and greasy, see your vet about an EPI test before changing anything else.</li>
  <li><strong>Weakening or wobbly back legs?</strong> Keep the dog lean and the protein generous — muscle over the spine and hindquarters is what keeps a Shepherd walking. Pair with joint support and your vet's guidance; food can't stop degenerative myelopathy but lean, well-muscled condition buys mobility.</li>
  <li><strong>Stiff or arthritic hips and elbows?</strong> Lean on joint support (glucosamine, chondroitin, omega-3) and keep weight down — fresh and cold-pressed recipes plus omega-3 help most.</li>
  <li><strong>No freezer space (and a big dog eats a lot)?</strong> Years (shelf-stable fresh), Pure Pet Food (air-dried) or Forthglade grain-free kibble all store in the cupboard and scale affordably for a large breed.</li>
  <li><strong>Fussy or fading appetite / worn teeth?</strong> Fresh or air-dried wins on palatability, moisture and soft texture — Years and Butternut Box are the most tempting, or use Butternut as a topper to lift a kibble base.</li>
  <li><strong>On a budget?</strong> Pure Pet Food or Forthglade grain-free give excellent, digestible senior nutrition without the premium frozen-fresh price a big dog would otherwise rack up.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Senior German Shepherds vs Adult German Shepherds: What Changes</h2>

<p>If you've been feeding a good adult food, the senior shift is a recalibration rather than a reinvention. The digestibility-first, limited-ingredient, sensitive-gut brief stays exactly as it was — that never retires. What's added is <strong>fewer calories for the same or better protein</strong> (your Shepherd is moving less but needs muscle more than ever), a stronger tilt toward joint support, and a new priority no younger Shepherd diet has to think about: feeding to protect the hindquarters, where lean weight and muscle-sparing protein are the two levers that keep a dog with stiffening hips or early degenerative myelopathy on its feet. The big-dog economics that make full fresh feeding a stretch for this breed are the same as they always were — which is why shelf-stable fresh, air-dried and cold-pressed routes earn their place. We dig into the big-dog cost question in our <a href="/fresh-vs-kibble-cost-large-dogs/">fresh vs kibble cost guide for large dogs</a>. For the full breed picture across life stages, see our <a href="/best-dog-food-for-german-shepherds/">best dog food for German Shepherds guide</a>; for raising one from the start, our <a href="/best-food-for-german-shepherd-puppies/">best food for German Shepherd puppies guide</a> covers the lean-growth, joint-protecting feeding that pays off later; and for the wider senior view across breeds, our <a href="/best-senior-dog-food-uk/">best senior dog food guide</a> goes deeper on the science. Given the breed's delicate gut, our <a href="/best-dog-food-sensitive-stomach-uk/">sensitive stomach &amp; skin guide</a> is well worth a read too.</p>

<h2>How Much to Feed — and Transitioning a Senior German Shepherd</h2>

<p>Portion is where most senior Shepherds slip, and on this breed it isn't just about the waistline — it's about keeping weak or arthritic hindquarters from hauling extra weight, so feed calories, not cupfuls: our <a href="/how-much-to-feed-senior-dog/">how much to feed a senior dog guide</a> turns calorie needs into grams of kibble, wet or fresh, and the <a href="/dog-food-calculator/?breed=german-shepherds">dog food calculator</a> will prefill a typical German Shepherd weight for you. Split the daily ration across two or more smaller meals to respect the deep-chested bloat risk, never let a Shepherd gulp a single big bowl, and avoid vigorous exercise around mealtimes. When you change foods, switch over <strong>7–10 days</strong>, mixing increasing amounts of the new food into the old, and slow right down if you see loose stools — a sensitive Shepherd gut punishes sudden change. And whenever a senior German Shepherd shows hind-leg weakness, scuffing or wobble, a swollen hard belly with unproductive retching, weight loss despite a good appetite, or a noticeable change in stools or toileting, book a vet check promptly; at this age, and with this breed, food is only part of the picture.</p>

